Been coming here since the early 1990s, back when I was just a kid and my parents worked for Brooklyn Union Gas which was just on the corner of Montague and Cadman Plaza. Though I no longer live in Brooklyn, I make a point to come here at least once whenever I visit family that are still in town. Why? This is the quintessential diner experience from beginning to end. Portions are generous, pricing is affordable, the menu is of a decent size (lots of different options), and there are dozens of pictures hung on the walls from yesteryear throughout. I miss the jukebox, though - sucks that was removed.  Historically, I've always come here for the pasta dishes and their burgers - they've always hit the right spot no matter what time of day it was. Given how much the neighborhood has changed, it would be nice if they expanded their morning hours to catch the breakfast crowd, but that's just me being picky.  Overall, I highly recommend Happy Days Diner. They are a fixture in Downtown Brooklyn. Just about everything around it has changed, but they continue to hold the fort - there is a reason for that.
